{{About|a sociology-related concept of group action|the mathematical concept|group action}}
{{Refimprove|date=May 2010}}

In [[sociology]], a '''group action''' is a situation in which a number of [[Agency (philosophy)|agents]] take [[social action|action]] simultaneously in order to achieve a common goal; their actions are usually coordinated.

Group action will often take place when social agents realize they are more likely to achieve their goal when acting together rather than individually. Group action differs from [[group behaviour]]s, which are uncoordinated, and also from [[mass action (sociology)|mass action]]s, which are more limited in place.

Group action is more likely to occur when the individuals within the group feel a [[identity fusion|sense of unity with the group]], even in personally costly actions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Swann Jr|first1=William B.|title=Identity Fusion|journal=Current Directions in Psychological Science|date=2015|volume=24|doi=10.1177/0963721414551363|pages=52–57}}</ref>

